Layers of the TCP/IP Model

| Layer          | Function                                 | Common Protocols                 |
| -------------- | ---------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Application    | Provides services to user applications   | HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, DNS, SMTP, SSH |
| Transport      | Ensures end-to-end communication         | TCP, UDP                         |
| Internet       | Handles logical addressing and routing   | IP, ICMP, ARP                    |
| Network Access | Transfers data over the physical network | Ethernet, Wi-Fi                  |





Layer-by-Layer Explanation
1. Application Layer
Function

Provides network services directly to applications used by the user.

Examples
HTTP
HTTPS
FTP
DNS
SMTP
SSH
Real-world Example

When you open google.com, your browser communicates with the web server using HTTP or HTTPS.

2. Transport Layer
Function
Breaks data into segments.
Ensures reliable communication (TCP).
Provides faster communication when reliability is less important (UDP).
Protocols
TCP
UDP
Example
File download → TCP
Video streaming → UDP
3. Internet Layer
Function
Assigns logical IP addresses.
Finds the best route for packets.
Delivers packets between networks.
Protocols
IPv4
IPv6
ICMP
ARP
Device
Router
4. Network Access Layer
Function
Sends data over the physical network.
Uses MAC addresses.
Converts data into electrical, optical, or wireless signals.
Technologies
Ethernet
Wi-Fi
Fiber
MAC Address
Devices
Switch
Network Interface Card (NIC)
Data Flow Example

When you visit www.google.com:

The browser sends an HTTPS request (Application Layer).
TCP divides the data into segments (Transport Layer).
IP adds source and destination IP addresses (Internet Layer).
Ethernet or Wi-Fi transmits the data to the router (Network Access Layer).



TCP/IP vs OSI Model

| Feature              | TCP/IP                                          | OSI                                    |
| -------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Number of Layers     | 4                                               | 7                                      |
| Developed By         | DARPA                                           | ISO                                    |
| Practical Use        | Used on the Internet                            | Mainly a reference model               |
| Application Layer    | Combines Application, Presentation, and Session | Separate layers                        |
| Transport Layer      | TCP and UDP                                     | Transport                              |
| Internet Layer       | IP Routing                                      | Network                                |
| Network Access Layer | Data Link + Physical                            | Separate Data Link and Physical layers |


Advantages
Simple and practical.
Used worldwide.
Supports communication between different operating systems.
Scalable for networks of all sizes.
Reliable communication using TCP.
Efficient routing through IP.


